<li id="cite_note-Goldberg-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Goldberg_12-0" title="">^</a></b> Michelle Goldberg, <a href="http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/09/30/campus/index.html" class="external text" title="http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/2002/09/30/campus/index.html" rel="nofollow">"Mau-mauing the Middle East."</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Salon.com" title="Salon.com">Salon.com</a></i> <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2002-09-30"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="09-30"><a href="/wiki/September_30" title="September 30">September 30</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2002" title="2002">2002</a></span>, accessed <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2007-02-17"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="02-17"><a href="/wiki/February_17" title="February 17">February 17</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2007" title="2007">2007</a></span>, cites Dershowitz's perspective on his own support for Israel and Israeli-sponsored terror in the context of what some regarded then as a "chilly" academic environment for doing so in 2002: "'I'm one of the very, very few professors around the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> that vigorously speaks up on behalf of <a href="/wiki/Israel" title="Israel">Israel</a>, and I have gotten e-mails and calls from all over the world from students who feel chilled because no one speaks up for them.'" (page two of three pages).</li>
